item.caption: MRI thoracic spine w wo contrast limited (08/19/2016 1:36 PM)

td.paragraph: PROVIDED CLINICAL INDICATIONS:h/o osteo/ worsening pain
TECHNIQUE:Multiplanar, multisequence magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the
thoracic spine is performed before and after administration of contrast.
Precontrast T1 and T2 weighted sequences are obtained.T1 weighted sequences
are also performed after administration of contrast.
18 mL MultiHance Gadolinium based contrast is administered intravenously.
FINDINGS:Moderate spondylosis is seen throughout the thoracic spine. The cord
has normal signal intensity. There is increased edema and enhancement of the
T12 and L1 vertebral bodies but no endplate destruction. Fluid is seen in the
disc but no enhancement of the disc. There is a subacute inferior endplate
fracture of the T12 vertebral body seen on prior imaging. There is enhancement
of the paraspinous soft tissues but no abscess. Mild anterior dural enhancement
is seen but no epidural abscess.
No other area of enhancement or signal change in the thoracic spine.
IMPRESSION:Increased edema and enhancement of the T12 and L1 vertebral
bodies without endplate destruction or enhancement of the disc. Differential
considerations include atypical MR appearance of osteomyelitis without
significant discitis versus acute degenerative spondylosis with associated
marrow edema. Given that edema and enhancement have increased, consider
CT-guided sampling for microbiological cultures and sensitivity.
Subacute inferior endplate fracture of the T12 vertebral body.
Enhancement of the paraspinous soft tissues and the anterior dura of T12-L1 but
no epidural abscess or paraspinous abscess.
Interface, Rad Results In - 08/19/2016 2:04 PM PDT

Elevated D-Dimer levels suggest fibrinolysis of intravascular thrombi, causes of which include pulmonary embolism, DVT, post surgical wound healing and trauma. Elevated levels may also be seen in pregnancy, cancer, infection, and old age.
D-Dimer levels < 500 ng/mL FEU indicate a very low probability of intravascular thrombosis.The actual range for a normal population is 100-500 ng/mL FEU. The range stated above is set at a cut-off level of 500 ng/mL FEU and is optimized for sensitivity
to low levels of D-Dimer. Levels can be much higher in DIC, but evaluation should include other coagulation tests.

and/or kV
dose adjustments based on patient size.

accessed
using a LEFT lateral approach. 3 core biopsy samples were obtained. Needle
was
removed. Sterile dressing applied.

difficult
to arouse though vital signs remained stable.

Heeter
with an independent nurse observer for 60 minutes..
CONTRAST: None.

1. Successful CT guided T12-L1 bone biopsy.
